  "articleSummary": "This analytical article argues that traditional, fixed-choice priority fields (e.g., P1–P4) inevitably fail as organizations grow, leading to \"priority inflation\" where labels like \"P00\" become meaningless. The author uses a satirical \"startup story\" tone to critique the \"Engineering Theater\" of Jira-based backlog management, drawing a technical parallel to CSS `z-index` wars to illustrate how unbounded competition for attention breaks systems. Intended for engineering managers and developers, the piece advocates for dynamic alternatives such as neutral numeric scales, multidimensional scoring (e.g., MoSCoW), and the aggressive archiving of \"stale\" tickets to maintain focus on actionable work.",
